declarations.comments:
A convenient alias for setting the `content` property of a Lumi component

WARNING: This is for JS interop -- don't use this to unwrap Maybes!

Unsafely nulls out a value so the resulting html attributes are less noisy
Ex: `R.input { type: unsafeMaybeToNullableAttr Nothing }` avoids rendering
the `type` attribute while still validating the type of the Maybe's content
matches the type of the DOM field. It's only slightly safer than using

Sequential `SeqFormBuilder` used for asynchronously initializing some
piece of form data, invalidating the form and preventing the rendering of
subsequent fields while the supplied `Aff` is not completed.

For example:

```purescript
myForm = parallel do
  initializer mempty \props value -> do
    foo <- fetchDefaultFoo
    pure $ value
      { foo = foo
      , bar = props.bar
      }

  sequential ado
    foo <- focus (Proxy :: Proxy "foo") textbox
    bar <- focus (Proxy :: Proxy "bar") switch
    in { foo, bar }
```
declarations.title: initializer

`PartialIso` in `profunctor-lenses`, we use `Iso` here.

Caveat emptor, you get what you pay for if you pass in a dodgy
`Iso` here.
declarations.title: via

declarations.comments:
Listens for changes in a form's state and allows for performing
asynchronous effects and additional state changes.

The asynchronous effect is fired on every state change. Note that from a UI
perspective, the effect is not observably asynchronous: the asynchronous
action is executed in the background, but the wrapped form's UI is not
responsive to the user until the action completes. To use this function
effectively, the supplied callback must return promptly. Setting some React
state in the callback would be appropriate but making network calls should
be done judiciously. Network calls can be justified if they are in response
to infrequent updates (e.g. selecting an item in a dropdown that causes
loading of data specific to that selection) but if the calls are in
response to every digit typed into a number input field for example, a user
may experience delays with their inputs and the backend will be hit
excessively.
declarations.title: listen

declarations.comments:
Traverse a tree bottom-up, removing all "internal" nodes (i.e. `Wrapper`
or `Node` constructors) which have empty `children` arrays. In the case
where there's nothing left in the tree after pruning, we return `Nothing`.

We need to perform the traversal bottom-up because, for example, a subtree
such as

```
let
  w children = Wrapper { key: Nothing, children }
in
  w [w []]
```

should be pruned, but a top-down operation would not be able to identify
such a subtree as prunable.
declarations.title: pruneTree

declarations.comments:
Lumi's tooltip component.

Tooltip positioning can get wonky depending upon the content size and
likely other factors. If the variant-driven defaults aren't sufficient,
a variant's absolute positioning may be overridden via CSS variables.

The CSS variables available for overriding currently are:

```
--lumi-tooltip-text-top
  Default: "-5px"
  Supported variants: "left", "right"
```

You may override these variables using the `style` field of `TooltipProps`:

```
tooltip
  { variant: "left"
  , style:
      css
        { "--lumi-tooltip-text-top": "-18px"
        -- ...
        }
  -- ...
  }
```
declarations.title: tooltip

declarations.comments:
A `Wizard` is a sequential computation of `FormBuilder`s, representing,
each one, a wizard step that can depend on the result of previous steps to
produce a final result.

`Wizard` is a monadic DSL that contains only a single instruction: `step`.
declarations.title: Wizard

`Wizard step`.
declarations.title: step

declarations.comments:
Revalidate a `Wizard`, returning the final result if, with the given
`value`, all steps produce valid results.
declarations.title: revalidate

declarations.comments:
`WizardStep` is a suspended `Wizard` computation, that is, a `Wizard`
whose execution has been stopped at some step. It can be thought of as a
`Wizard` zipper.
declarations.title: WizardStep

declarations.comments:
Retrieve the identifier for the focused step of a `WizardStep`.
Returns `Nothing` if the `WizardStep` represents a finalized `Wizard`.
declarations.title: stepIdentifier

declarations.comments: Lifts a `Wizard` into a `WizardStep` that focuses on its first step.
declarations.title: liftStep

declarations.comments:
Resume a suspended `WizardStep`, if the current step produces a valid
result, returning either the next `WizardStep` or the final result.
declarations.title: resumeStep

declarations.comments: Return the previous step, if there is one.
declarations.title: previousStep

declarations.comments:

declarations.title: gotoStep

declarations.comments: A component that renders a `WizardStep` (a suspended `Wizard`).

declarations.comments:
`loadingContent` sets the content to display while a link button
is in its loading state. The size of the link button will always
fit the larger content, regardless which state it's in.
declarations.title: loadingContent

declarations.comments:
A form submit button. This helper takes the button state
as an argument because a form's buttons are generally
tied to the validity and `onSubmit` behavior of the form,
rather than providing an `onPress` action to the button
itself.
declarations.title: submit

declarations.comments:
A form reset button. This helper takes the button state
as an argument because a form's buttons are generally
tied to the validity and `onSubmit` behavior of the form,
rather than providing an `onPress` action to the button
itself.
declarations.title: reset

declarations.comments:
Set the button state. Generally you'll want to use `submit` or
`reset` instead, but this can still be useful for `onPress`
buttons which need to be disabled while some page state is
invalid or share in a collective page loading state.

Note: When a page is in a loading state, any buttons which
  were _not_ interacted with should be set to `Disabled`, not
  `Loading`. A row of buttons containing the same spinner
  looks strange. You also do not need to track which button
  was interacted with, usually, because the `onPress` loading
  state will override this one within the button pressed.
declarations.title: state

declarations.comments:
A button with customized `onPress` behavior. The button will
automatically display a loading state while the action is in-progress.
Using `onPress` on a button multiple times chains the effects together
from the first applied, out.
declarations.title: onPress

declarations.comments:
Like `onPress` but allows additional control over how the provided
behavior interacts with any existing behavior.
declarations.title: onPress'

declarations.comments:
Auto-focus this button. Only one element on the page should
have `autoFocus` set at a time.
declarations.title: autoFocus

declarations.comments:
Set `ariaLabel` when the button content is not legible text,
for example a button that only contains an X might set this
label to "Close".
declarations.title: ariaLabel

declarations.comments:
An image has no size restrictions
will respect the image's original aspect ratio
declarations.title: image

declarations.comments:
A thumbnail can support size restrictions
will always have a square aspect ratio
declarations.title: thumbnail

declarations.comments:
we support two sizing scales for thumbnails
avatars use a smaller scale, whereas all other images use the above size scale
declarations.title: smallAvatar

declarations.comments: restricted to only Image
declarations.title: resize

declarations.comments: restricted to only Thumbnail
declarations.title: round

declarations.comments:
Adds a listener to an event target. The boolean argument indicates whether
the listener should be added for the "capture" phase.
declarations.title: addPassiveEventListener

declarations.comments:
Removes a listener to an event target. The boolean argument indicates
whether the listener should be removed for the "capture" phase.
declarations.title: removePassiveEventListener

declarations.comments:
Inline piece of text whose `content` prop is a `String`. Elements of this
component should preferentially be used only where an inline piece of text
with no bottom margin is expected.

For block-level, independent text elements, please use `paragraph`,
`paragraph_`, or the header components defined in this module.
declarations.title: text

declarations.comments:
The `c` type parameter lets us constrain the type of component to which
a text modifier may be applied: `Text`, `Header` or any.
declarations.title: TextModifier

declarations.comments: A variant of `paragraph` whose `content` prop is a `String`.
declarations.title: paragraph_

declarations.comments:
A `paragraph` is a block-level element that contains text and/or other
inline-level elements, such as images. Paragraphs also define a bottom
margin so that multiple paragraphs in a column can read nicely with proper
spacing.

Paragraphs are used for laying out chunks of text as concrete, individual
and independent elements in a page.
declarations.title: paragraph

declarations.comments: Lift a themed set of styles into a `StyleModifier` for composition with other modifiers.
declarations.title: style

declarations.comments: Lift a static set of styles into a `StyleModifier` for composition with other modifiers.
declarations.title: style_

declarations.comments: Lift an array of themed styles into a `StyleModifier` for composition with other modifiers.
declarations.title: styles

declarations.comments: Lift an array of static styles into a `StyleModifier` for composition with other modifiers.
declarations.title: styles_

declarations.comments:
Flatten a `PropsModifier` and extract the Emotion styles for use with `React.Basic.Emotion.element`.
This function is mainly used inside component implementations where the `LumiComponent` boundary
gives way to DOM components or other `ReactComponent`s.
declarations.title: toCSS

declarations.comments: Relative to 1% of the width of the viewport.
declarations.title: vw

declarations.comments: Relative to 1% of viewport's smaller dimension.
declarations.title: vmin

declarations.comments: Relative to 1% of viewport's larger dimension.
declarations.title: vmax

declarations.comments: Relative to 1% of the height of the viewport.
declarations.title: vh

declarations.comments:
Use a variable name as a property.

Define a property somewhere:
```
css { "--color-primary": color blue }
```

Use the var:
```
css { color: var "--color-primary" }
```
declarations.title: var

declarations.comments: Relative to font-size of the root element.
declarations.title: rem

declarations.comments:
Pixels and subpixels.

WARNING: Approaches to subpixel rendering vary among browser
implementations. This means that non-integer pixel values may be displayed
differently in different browsers.
declarations.title: px'

declarations.comments:
Pixels. This function does not take a `Number` because approaches to
subpixel rendering vary among browser implementations.
declarations.title: px

declarations.comments: Points (1pt = 1/72 of 1in)
declarations.title: pt

declarations.comments: Relative to the parent element.
declarations.title: percent

declarations.comments: Picas (1pc = 12 pt)
declarations.title: pc

declarations.comments:
Create a unitless `Number` property.

Wherever units may be specified, use unit combinators like `px`
or `em` instead.
declarations.title: num

declarations.comments: Milimeters
declarations.title: mm

declarations.comments:
Create a unitless `Int` property.

Wherever units may be specified, use unit combinators like `px`
or `em` instead.
declarations.title: int

declarations.comments: Inches (1in ≈ 2.54cm)
declarations.title: inches

declarations.comments: Relative to the x-height of the current font (rarely used).
declarations.title: ex

declarations.comments:
Relative to the font-size of the element (2em means 2 times the size of
the current font).
declarations.title: em

declarations.comments:
Create a `JSX` node from a `ReactComponent`, by providing the props.

This function is identical to `React.Basic.element` plus Emotion's
`css` prop.
declarations.title: elementKeyed

declarations.comments: Centimeters
declarations.title: cm

declarations.comments: Relative to the width of the "0" (zero) character.
declarations.title: ch

declarations.comments:
Create a style modifier that, only in a desktop-sized screen, applies the
styles accumulated in the modifier passed in as argument.

NOTE: the value passed in as argument must be a props modifier that touches
no component-specific props, a property that currently defines style
modifiers.
declarations.title: onDesktop

declarations.comments: Guard a style so that it's only applied in a desktop resolution.
declarations.title: desktopQuery

declarations.comments:
Create a style modifier that, only in a mobile-sized screen, applies the
styles accumulated in the modifier passed in as argument.

NOTE: the value passed in as argument must be a props modifier that touches
no component-specific props, a property that currently defines style
modifiers.
declarations.title: onMobile

declarations.comments: Guard a style so that it's only applied in a mobile screen resolution.
declarations.title: mobileQuery
